I’ve given you snippets of my weekend in Silverton, Colorado but I didn’t say why I was there having all this fun, some of it TYPE 2 fun!

I went to @tellurideski first to ski with my friends @ultracraig32 and @azwish, who made me ski a very-steep-to-me slope. Whew! My heart was racing the entire time! It was exhilarating though. And I appreciate their patience as I navigated that slope. Then I headed out to Silverton, at the beginning of this massive snowstorm.

Last year, @sethaehrlich invited me out to give the keynote at the @sosoutreach MLK Powder Challenge, a fundraising weekend whose dollars go to supporting youth not only by introducing them to skiing or snowboarding, but also providing mentorship, employment and internship opportunities, and the social and cultural capital that comes with immersing oneself in a culture that skews exclusive. 

@phil_henderson , the expedition leader of the first all black team to summit Everest @fullcircleeverest, was the keynote this year and I had many conversations with him around equity and continuing and providing opportunities in the outdoors for those in our community. He spoke about the importance of opening doors, mentoring, and being curious and open to others’ stories. He is PHENOMENAL 

SOS does the work in a pretty unique way and I attended the weekend as a guest. I tried a new thing —backcountry skiing, and it was super hard. Skinning (walking with yer skis) was very tough for me at 11,000 feet as was simply remaining upright while skiing in very deep powder, but I did it anyway—the guides from @sanjuan.expeditions were incredible, patient, wonderful. And this is how SOS treats the kids they support. They introduce them to these incredible sports, the culture, the challenges of learning more and more difficult skills, support them, and in so doing provide LIFE CHANGING opportunities. These kids and young adults flourish. It’s kind of like a Prep for Prep of skiing. The experience and the people stay with you forever, and your life trajectory is changed.

Boundary request— not looking for any advice on technique here. Chill, it was my first time doing this. Thanks.

Have you been to @Keystone_Resort? 
At just under two hours from Denver, it is a perfect wonderland for those who love being outside.

First, it’s huge! There are beginner trails like the 3.5 mile long Schoolmarm (super fun!), to intermediate ones like Mozart (my fave!) to more steep and mogul-filled choose-your-own-adventure type runs!  I took a lesson with such an amazing instructor and not only did he impart valuable skier’s wisdom and skills, he showed me around three peaks. What a treat! (more on my lesson later!)

Hungry? There are many options for fueling yourself between incredible runs. (Did you know you get 20% off of resort restaurants when you show your @EpicPass?

If you want to explore off mountain, you can go on a sleigh ride that includes a sumptuous dinner in a cabin (did this!), or eat at the high end and delicious Keystone Ranch while it is dumping snow outside (did this too!). If your downhill legs are tired, you can Nordic ski in a beautiful expanse and then hop in the hot tub at Keystone Lodge and Spa, readying your body for the next day of surprises (also did this.) 

There was so much to do and explore. I left there—legs deliciously sore, belly and heart full, Nordic skiing curiosity piqued, and another Epic Pass Adventure checked off!

I accept the increasing amount of gray hairs on my scalp as markers of wisdom and general coolness, but I definitely want to be aware of anything that affects my health specifically as a maturing female-identifying person. 

InsideTracker has added more biomarkers specific to women, so we can keep our eye on even more important markers of our health—Estradiol- a potent form of estrogen, Progesterone-a hormone important for reproductive health, and TSH-Thyroid Stimulating Hormone—a sensitive marker of thyroid production. As women age, we have an increased risk of lower than optimal thyroid function.

I’m interested finding out what these particular marker levels are for me—perhaps they might explain a changing body, or a difference energy level, or what I’m kicking %^& at training again after a long lull.

Now is the time to jump on the wagon (it has really ALWAYS been the time), because we have more and more scientific resources aimed at studying and understanding women’s health. I can’t wait to see what these particular biomarkers are for me at my next blood draw. 

What would it be like if we all were super-knowledgeable about the things that are happening in our bodies throughout all stages of our lives, and had more than myths to lean on. It could be so cool. Wait, IT IS AVAILABLE TO US NOW.

TLDR: WE HAD A GOOD-ASS, LIFE-CHANGING TIME IN THE ALPS. 

I’ve been fortunate to partner with several small and fantastic tour companies and @runthealps by @doog_in_chamonix continues a special trajectory—one of extending what many think are experiences reserved for thin, fast folks to those who run trails but maybe a little or a lot more slowly. We got to see the same incredible vistas,to challenge ourselves in new ways, to eat raclette and rösti, have our bartender pour us drinks based on our personalities, to rest our sore limbs in expansive spas complete with ice caves, we immersed ourselves in several different cultures and got to speak ALL THE LANGUAGES. We saw two sides of Mont Blanc, we traversed the glaciers by cable car, sang karaoke I Wanna Dance with Somebody and More Than Words in an Italian restaurant. Some of us had rabbit for the first time. We drank countless bottles of excellent wine and really good beer. 

We passed by folks making the pilgrimage from Canterbury through the Alps to Apulia, Italy (that is A LOT of climbing!) and many doing the Tour de Mont Blanc. 

We made new friends and reconnected with old ones and talked about changes to make in our lives, and how we appreciated the opportunity to be in such beautiful natural spaces moving and even loving our bodies as they did what bodies do. 

We were guided by three phenomenal guides—Emily, who some of us called the Mother Abbess, Sam @hill_adventures , @mountaineeringmike the Mountain Goat, and @mountaineeringmike, who we gave the trail name Ted Lasso ❤️❤️. They cared for us, pushed a little when necessary, but mostly allowed us to move at our own trail running paces (AS IN A LOTTA HIKING UP AND RUNNING DOWN).

The conversations we had were scintillating and hilarious, deep and probing, light and sometimes existential. There’s something about moving up, through, on, around, and down mountains that does something to you and allows you to let your guard down a bit. 

There is so much more to tell. But lemme process a bit more!

Just came off of three weeks of pretty intense stuff— @lululemon FURTHER training camp, ambassador product co-creation and training, and a week in Northern Idaho with my coach and friend @mikerunsidaho who made me do crazy goat-like climbing on steep mountains. 

I never thought I’d be doing any of this, including, multiple really cool and surreal photo shoots a year, but here we are. I don’t think anyone who knew me in high school is surprised, but I’m still surprised, delighted, grateful (and also overwhelmed!) every day for what I get to do to help change the narratives about people who live in plus sizes or fat bodies. 
I’ve been reading a lot — namely @tressiemcphd, @kate_manne, and some other peer reviewed papers I found in the Journal of Orthopaedic & Sports Physical Therapy—on our society’s obsession with shrinking people in larger bodies—you know for societal acceptance— and the shame, disgust, rigid opinions, assumptions, and attitudes (note that I did not say factual evidence) associated with the lifestyles and perceived health statuses of fat people. Whew! It’s a lot to digest. 
 
Here is a little glimpse into what someone who passed me on a shoot one day referred to as fake running 😂😂😂😂. Like, how do you think commercial photography and ads work? It’s hill repeats boo—OVER AND OVER AGAIN.

Anyway: I’m super stoked to be part of the Lululemon FURTHER project. For the first time in my experience, the questions won’t be how soon will fatness kill this body; how soon will this person become diabetic; how soon will they break their knees—the questions will be how far can this body go, how will this person’s life be enhanced by their love of covering distance with their own two feet; how can this person inspire and motivate others to find what their FURTHER is? I’m so excited to not be the subject of pathology, but one of hope and expectation.
 
This is revolutionary.
